segments.text: Bill Scott, forest ranger.
Today we present the final program in this series on forest conservation featuring Bill Scott, forest ranger.
Our scene is the little ranger station deep within the Beaver Dam Forest.
It is here that Ranger Bill has asked Joe and Sam to meet him and his niece June on the boy's last day in the forest.
As we join them, it's apparent that something exciting is in the air.
Though he tries to hide it, Ranger Bill has a strange tenseness about him.
His glance keeps darting out of the window toward the tops of the trees which are being whipped about wildly by a strong, unrelenting wind.

Sitting at the Ranger Station radio with receiver wide open is the Beaverdam fire dispatcher, Mac, who listens quietly as Ranger Bill tells his young friends of the danger which faces the forest this day.
I might as well tell you.
forest and the air are very dry today, boys.
We're up against what we might call a bad fire day.
And that's why I asked you to meet me here.
Yes, I'm standing by for anything that might happen.
But, Ranger Bill, there's been no rain since that big storm we got caught in.
And that means there's been no lightning either.
I've always thought that lightning... Yes, I know.
You've always thought that lightning causes most of our forest fires.
Is that it, Joe?
Yes, sir.
Well, that's something you ought to get straight in your mind right now, son.
Lightning is bad at times.
especially in the West during the summer storms.
But, now, get this.
Lightning isn't responsible for more than one-tenth of all the forest fires we have in this country year after year.
Golly, you mean that all the rest, nine out of every ten fires, are started by human beings like us here?
That's right, Sam.
Nine out of every ten forest fires are caused by man.
And most of them start simply as a result of carelessness or thoughtlessness.
Somebody tosses a lighted match or cigarette away.
A camper leaves his campfire without being sure it's dead out.
Things like that.
Well, that's the sort of thing we're on guard against today.

That's right.

Sure.

Yes.

Just off Blackhawk Trail.
Blackhawk Trail?

Okay, boys, let's go.
Uncle Bill, I want to go too.
I won't get in the way, I promise.
I'll carry water or messages, anything.
Oh, please let me go, Uncle Bill.
Well...
All right, June.

Come on.
Come on, let's go.
Come on, let's go.
All right, boys, you can stop here.

What do we do?
Well, let's size up things, first of all.
Now, I want you to keep your heads, boys.
Stay calm and don't get excited.
Oh, we're not scared, Ranger Bill.
Not with you here.
Oh, fine.
Now, here's the way it looks for me.
We came here just about at the head or front of the fire.
That's whipping along pretty fast, but if the wind doesn't get any stronger, we should be able to hold the fire until the other firefighters get here.
What about Daisy, Uncle Bill?
Well, that pasture of Daisy's is about a quarter of a mile behind us, June.

If we do that, Daisy will be safe.

Now, Joe, you and Sam have those fire rigs I gave you, don't you?
Well, we'll work together then.

What do you want us to do?
I've got this water pump strapped to my back, so I'll go first, Sam.
I'll spray water all along the front of the fire.
That'll help cool it a bit, but it won't stop it.
Now, you and Joe follow right close behind me, you got it?

How deep down, Ranger Bill?
Well, right down to the dirt, Joe.

The fire's feeding on leaves and twigs, you see, and if you take its food away, it's bound to die down.
Lucky thing for us, though, it's still a ground fire and hasn't jumped up to the tops of the trees.
Oh, a crown fire would be mighty bad medicine.

I know.

All right.

And so we conclude this series of programs on forest conservation featuring Bill Scott, forest ranger.
Participating in this series have been the following members of the radio workshop of the New York City Board of Education.
Stan Gorel was Joe.
Sam was played by Gerald Sandler.
Barbara Tushner was cast in the role of June.
Sound effects have been handled by Joseph Skolnick, with Morton Siegel as his assistant.
And music was arranged by Henry Hahn.
